Given the high HE operating temperature (reported in Table 1), thermal radiation heat transfer was also accounted for. First, a discrete ordinate method was compared with the surface-to-surface (S2S) radiation method [20]. Eventually, the latter was chosen thanks to its proven accuracy and computationally affordability in comparison to the discrete ordinate method. Indeed, the S2S is suitable to replicate radiative heat transfer among opaque grey bodies through transparent media, like dry air or pure nitrogen in the range of emission frequency of temperatures encountered in engineering applications. All surfaces were considered in the calculation of the view factors. For all solid walls the same emissivity value was set, ϵ=\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\epsilon =$$\end{document} 0.7 for ZrO2 and ϵ=\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\epsilon =$$\end{document} 0.6 for Si-SiC. Instead, for the inlet and outlet sections an emissivity value of 0 was imposed excluding therefore the onset of additional radiative heat transfer coming from regions out of the computational domain under analysis (e.g., inlet and outlet ducts, flow distributors). View factors were calculated using a face-to-face approach, applying a cluster for each surface, i.e., no clustering is applied. The radiation equation was solved for each iteration of the energy equation. The top and bottom parting sheets, as well as the lattice structures surfaces, were assumed smooth and a no-slip condition was applied. Symmetry condition was considered on the lateral vertical surfaces.

